## The Asymmetry Premium

The pear diamond charges a price premium over the oval despite offering less face-up coverage per carat. At 1ct G-VS2 GIA, pear starts at [$3,150](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28393670?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) versus oval at [$2,887](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28476955?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — a $263 gap. At the same time, the oval delivers roughly 16% more face-up area per carat at their respective standard L:W ratios.

This inversion — paying more for less visible coverage — is The Asymmetry Premium: the market price of the pear's unique silhouette.

Why does the premium exist? Three reasons:

**1. Rarity of well-cut pears.** A properly proportioned pear with centered point symmetry, even wing balance, and controlled bowtie is genuinely harder to produce than an oval. The rough diamond yield rate for top-quality pears is lower. That production challenge flows through to the price.

**2. Celebrity and cultural demand.** Pear engagement rings worn by high-profile figures generate cyclical demand spikes that ratchet prices slightly above what pure supply/demand would predict.

**3. Distinctive positioning.** The pear's asymmetrical silhouette is inherently rarer than the oval's symmetrical curves. Rarity commands premium regardless of physical size.

What The Asymmetry Premium means for buyers: you are paying for the aesthetic, not the diamond. A pear buyer who wants the teardrop silhouette specifically is getting fair value for the price. A pear buyer who simply wants an elongated diamond without a specific preference for the pointed tip is overpaying by $263 at 1ct for a shape that is also smaller in face-up area.

## The Point Protection Tax

The pear's pointed tip is its most distinctive feature — and its most structurally demanding one. Unlike an oval, which has a smooth, continuously curved girdle with no points of concentration, a pear's tip tapers to the thinnest section of the entire stone. That geometric taper creates two compulsory costs that every pear buyer pays regardless of the stone they select.

**Cost 1: The V-prong mandatory setting upgrade.** A standard prong placed at or near a pear's point provides inadequate contact at the thinnest part of the stone. A V-prong — a single prong bent into a V-shape that cups both sides of the tip — is the industry-standard solution that protects the point from lateral impact. V-prong pear settings cost $200–$400 more than comparable oval settings because of the additional precision required to manufacture and install the V-shaped tip.

**Cost 2: The tip clarity inspection burden.** Any inclusion sitting within 2mm of the pear's point carries dual risk: it is more visible at the stone's thinnest section (light passes through a thinner layer of diamond) and it structurally weakens the most fragile part of the stone. This means pear buyers must specifically confirm no feathers, chips, or clouds are present near the tip — a check that requires watching a high-resolution 360° video of the specific stone, not reading the GIA report. Most GIA report inclusions are plotted but not location-coded for "near point" risk. The evaluation burden falls entirely on the buyer.

**Cost 3 (hidden): The mandatory video audit.** The pear's point symmetry — whether the tip is centered on the stone's long axis or offset to one side — cannot be determined from a GIA certificate or a static product photo. Crooked or offset points destroy the stone's visual balance. Confirming point alignment requires watching the stone rotate in video. For buyers who skip the video step, the return rate on pear diamonds is meaningfully higher than for oval or round.

The total Point Protection Tax at 1ct: $200–$400 in V-prong setting premium plus the time and diligence cost of the video audit. The oval has no equivalent mandatory cost.

> **Farzana's Expert Take:** I have reviewed thousands of pear diamonds, and the buyers who skip the video audit consistently regret it. A GIA report can show G-VS2 Ideal cut and still produce a pear with a visibly crooked point and a dominant bowtie that kills the stone's brilliance. The video audit is not optional — it is the core of pear diamond due diligence. Block 30 minutes, watch the stone rotate, check the point alignment and the bowtie in the shoulder area. If the retailer doesn't provide a 360° video, do not buy the stone. Blue Nile's "Ideal" pears include HD video on every listing.

